The given input appears to be an example of a Prime Knot. A prime knot is a closed loop of edges that meet at vertices where three or more strands intersect. In this case there are 13 vertices and 12 edges which makes it a very simple example. To convert from Gauss Code to Dowker-Thistlethwaite code you would need to perform a sequence of moves on each edge of the knot as described below:
* Move along the edge until you reach the first crossing.
* At the crossing look to see if the top strand goes over (1) or under (−1) the bottom strand. If it goes over record 1, if it goes under record −1.
* After one crossing move along the top strand until you find another crossing. Repeat step two for this crossing.
* Continue moving along the top strand making note of every time it crosses over or under another strand, noting the sign (+/-) of each intersection until you return to your starting point (the vertex). Here end of this edge has been reached.
* Perform steps 2–5 for all other edges of the knot.

The resulting list of signs (+/-) is your Gauss Code. You can then use an algorithm such as the Alexander Polynomial or Jones Matrix to compute the corresponding knot polynomial, V(t), where t=−1 is the unknot. Or, alternatively, you could manually transform the Gauss Code into the Tables of Prime and Composite Knots looking for a match. If the transformation results in a composite knot you may have accidentally introduced Torsion (a twisted component) during construction of your prime knot. If so simply undo any twists and try again.
